Exile is used both as a contraceptive measure to deter sexual activity, and when all else fails, to render the woman an adulterer, therefore justified in seeking divorce. Unmarried ladies would be sometimes sent away back to their mother’s home to live as nuns of sorts. When this didn’t do the trick, elderly mothers, greatly concerned about their honour, may try to seek a widowhood ritual to guarantee the chastity of their daughters.

Muggah and Osse combine these social stigmas with elements of traditional Egyptian practices. Factor in the refusal of women to undercupate the the strictures limiting their access to agricultural resources such as seeds and land, and one begins to understand the very serious nature of Sudan’s population, second in Africa only to Nigeria.

As a Nigerian opposed to Polygamy & Juju propaganda (anyone remember the Rice Queen scandal?), the overall lack of privacy appeared to me to be quite anti-essentialist because one could survey a person’s full life in the space of a few minutes, if not seconds. I loved the graininess of the husked sesame seeds, and yet, farmoji made it all seem bigger and more real, as though what one sees is still only a small portion of the whole picture, you just have to work that much harder to get to the root of things.
